<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Meteo on Dériveur - FFV4</title><link>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/</link><description>Recent content in Meteo on Dériveur - FFV4</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><atom:link href="https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Circulation générale</title><link>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/general_circulation/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/general_circulation/</guid><description>Circulation générale # Le soleil nous fournit la quasi-totalité de notre énergie. Le bilan énergétique de la Terre est nul: la Terre renvoi dans l’espace toute l’énergie qu’elle reçoit. Cependant,l’énergie reçue par la Terre n’est pas uniforme selon la latitude. L’équateur reçoit plus d’énergie que les pôles. Cela va créer des zones plus chaudes et des zones plus froides.Les masses d’air chaudes vont monter (zone d’ascendance) et les masses d’air froides vont descendre (zone de subsidence) à cause de leurs propriétés thermiques.</description></item><item><title>Le vent</title><link>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/wind/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/wind/</guid><description>Le vent est un flux d’air. Il se déplace globalement des hautes pressions vers les basses pressions. Plus la différence (gradient) de pression est importante (pour une distance donnée), plus le vent est fort. Le vent se déplace parallèlement aux isobares (sans tenir compte des frottements): c’est le vent géostrophique : équilibre entre les forces de pression et la force de Coriolis. Les frottements sont dus à la surface terrestre.</description></item><item><title/><link>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/air_volumes/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/air_volumes/</guid><description/></item><item><title/><link>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/clouds/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/clouds/</guid><description/></item><item><title/><link>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/frontology/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/frontology/</guid><description/></item><item><title/><link>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/isobaric_map/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/isobaric_map/</guid><description/></item><item><title/><link>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/local_weather/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/local_weather/</guid><description/></item><item><title/><link>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/waves_and_swell/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/waves_and_swell/</guid><description/></item><item><title/><link>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/weather_associated_with_a_perturbation/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/weather_associated_with_a_perturbation/</guid><description/></item><item><title/><link>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/weather_report/</link><pubDate>Mon, 01 Jan 0001 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://armandfardeau.github.io/dinghy-ffv4/docs/meteorology/weather_report/</guid><description/></item></channel></rss>